<!-- SECTION 1 — THE FACTORING PROBLEM -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s1">
<div class="section-num">Section 01</div>
<h2>The Factoring Problem</h2>

<p>At the heart of modern internet security lies a simple mathematical observation: it is easy to multiply two large prime numbers together, but apparently very hard to factor the result back into its prime factors.</p>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Definition — Integer Factoring Problem</div>
  Given a composite integer n, find its prime factors. That is, find primes p₁, p₂, … such that n = p₁ · p₂ · ….
</div>

<h3>Why does this matter?</h3>

<p>The RSA cryptosystem — used to secure email, banking, and most web traffic — relies entirely on the hardness of factoring. The RSA scheme works as follows:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Key generation:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Pick two large primes p, q (each ~500 bits). Compute n = p · q (~1024 bits).
      Publish n as the public key. Keep p and q secret.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Security relies on:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      If an attacker can factor n, they recover p and q and break the encryption.
      Classically, the best known algorithm requires O(e<sup>b<sup>1/3</sup></sup>) steps for a b-bit number — <strong>sub-exponential but not polynomial</strong>.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Trivial approach:</strong> Try all primes less than √n. For n with b bits, √n ≈ 2<sup>b/2</sup>, so this needs ~2<sup>b/2</sup> trials. For b = 1024, this is ~2<sup>512</sup> — utterly infeasible.
</div>

<h3>Special easy cases</h3>

<p>Not all factoring problems are hard. Two cases have efficient classical solutions:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Case 1:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">n is even → immediately factor out 2 repeatedly</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Case 2:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">n = a<sup>b</sup> for some integers → use binary search on b and Newton's method</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>The key insight of Shor's algorithm:</strong> for the general case, we can reduce factoring to a completely different problem — <em>finding the order</em> of an element in modular arithmetic — and the QFT solves this efficiently.
</div>

