<!-- SECTION 2 — REDUCTION TO ORDER-FINDING -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s2">
<div class="section-num">Section 02</div>
<h2>Reducing Factoring to Order-Finding</h2>

<p>Shor's brilliant insight is to reduce the factoring problem to a very different problem in number theory called <em>order finding</em>. Let us first define what we mean by "order".</p>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Definition — Order in Modular Arithmetic</div>
  Given integers x and n with gcd(x, n) = 1 (they share no common factor), the <strong>order</strong> of x modulo n is the smallest positive integer r such that:
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">
    <div class="eq"><span>x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1</span></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Modular arithmetic reminder:</strong> "a mod n" means the remainder when a is divided by n. For example, 7 mod 5 = 2, because 7 = 1·5 + 2. And ab mod n = (a mod n)(b mod n), which we use extensively.
</div>

<h3>The Shor algorithm — overview</h3>

<p>Here is the complete algorithm. Steps ①, ③, ④ are easy classically. Only step ② is hard classically but easy quantumly.</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--accent);">① Pick x</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Choose a random x ∈ &#123;2, 3, …, n−1&#125;.<br>
      Compute gcd(x, n). If gcd(x, n) > 1: we got lucky — x itself is a factor of n. <strong>STOP.</strong><br>
      Otherwise proceed.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--red);">② Order-finding</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Find the smallest r > 0 such that <strong>x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1</strong>.<br>
      This is the hard step — solved by the QFT.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--orange);">③ Check</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      If r is odd → go back to ①.<br>
      If (x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1) mod n = 0 → go back to ①.<br>
      Otherwise proceed to ④.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--green);">④ Extract factors</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">gcd(x<sup>r/2</sup> − 1, n)</span> and <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">gcd(x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1, n)</span> are non-trivial factors of n.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Example: factor n = 15</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">① Pick x=2:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">gcd(2, 15) = 1 ✓ (continue)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">② Order of 2 mod 15:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      2¹ mod 15 = 2<br>
      2² mod 15 = 4<br>
      2³ mod 15 = 8<br>
      2⁴ mod 15 = <span class="c-g">16 mod 15 = 1</span> ✓ → r = 4
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">③ Check:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      r = 4 is even ✓<br>
      (x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1) mod n = (2² + 1) mod 15 = 5 ≠ 0 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">④ Factors:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      gcd(x<sup>r/2</sup> − 1, n) = gcd(2² − 1, 15) = gcd(3, 15) = <span class="c-g">3</span><br>
      gcd(x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1, n) = gcd(2² + 1, 15) = gcd(5, 15) = <span class="c-g">5</span><br>
      So 15 = 3 × 5 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

