<!-- SECTION 3 — WHY IT WORKS (PROOF) -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s3">
<div class="section-num">Section 03</div>
<h2>Why the Algorithm Works — The Proof</h2>

<p>Why do gcd(x<sup>r/2</sup> ± 1, n) give factors of n? This requires a careful argument. Let us go through it step by step.</p>

<h3>Setting up the algebra</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Start from:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1 means x<sup>r</sup> = q·n + 1 for some integer q</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Rearrange:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">x<sup>r</sup> − 1 = q·n &nbsp;&nbsp; so <strong>n divides (x<sup>r</sup> − 1)</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Factor (r even):</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      x<sup>r</sup> − 1 = (x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1)(x<sup>r/2</sup> − 1) = q·n<br>
      <span class="eq-note">So the product (x<sup>r/2</sup>+1)(x<sup>r/2</sup>−1) is divisible by n.</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Where are the factors of n?</h3>

<p>We want to show that n splits its factors between (x<sup>r/2</sup>−1) and (x<sup>r/2</sup>+1). We argue by ruling out the alternatives:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--red);">Argument 1:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      <strong>n cannot divide (x<sup>r/2</sup> − 1) entirely.</strong><br>
      If it did, then (x<sup>r/2</sup> − 1) mod n = 0, meaning x<sup>r/2</sup> mod n = 1.<br>
      But r was defined as the <em>smallest</em> positive integer with x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1.<br>
      If x<sup>r/2</sup> mod n = 1, then r/2 would work as a smaller order — contradiction!
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--red);">Argument 2:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      <strong>n cannot divide (x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1) entirely.</strong><br>
      We explicitly check this in step ③ and restart if (x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1) mod n = 0.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--green);">Conclusion:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Some factors of n go into (x<sup>r/2</sup> − 1) and the remaining factors go into (x<sup>r/2</sup> + 1).<br>
      Therefore: <strong>gcd(x<sup>r/2</sup> ± 1, n) are non-trivial factors of n</strong>. □
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>Why gcd?</strong> The greatest common divisor gcd(a, n) extracts exactly the factors that a and n share. If a = x<sup>r/2</sup>−1 contains some (but not all) prime factors of n, then gcd(a, n) returns exactly those shared factors — a non-trivial factorization of n.
</div>

<h3>How often does the algorithm succeed?</h3>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Probability of success:</strong> For a random x, the probability that the order r is even AND (x<sup>r/2</sup>+1) mod n ≠ 0 is at least 1 − 1/2<sup>k−1</sup> where k is the number of distinct prime factors of n. For n = p·q (RSA), the success probability per trial is at least 1/2. On average, only 2–3 rounds are needed.
</div>

