<!-- SECTION 4 — ORDER → PERIOD FINDING -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s4">
<div class="section-num">Section 04</div>
<h2>Reformulating as Period Finding</h2>

<p>The order-finding problem has an elegant reformulation as a period-finding problem — and this is where the Fourier transform becomes the natural tool.</p>

<h3>The function f(ℓ)</h3>

<p>Define the function:</p>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">The modular exponentiation function</div>
  <div class="math-block">
    <div class="eq"><span>f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ℓ = 0, 1, 2, …</span></div>
  </div>
  Note that x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1 implies that x<sup>ℓ+r</sup> mod n = x<sup>ℓ</sup> · x<sup>r</sup> mod n = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n = f(ℓ).<br>
  Therefore <strong>f is periodic with period r</strong>: f(ℓ + r) = f(ℓ) for all ℓ.
</div>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Proof of periodicity:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      f(ℓ + r) = x<sup>ℓ+r</sup> mod n = (x<sup>ℓ</sup> · x<sup>r</sup>) mod n<br>
      = (x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n) · (x<sup>r</sup> mod n) mod n &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">[product rule for mod]</span><br>
      = (x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n) · 1 = f(ℓ) &nbsp;&nbsp; ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Example: x=2, n=15</h3>

<canvas id="cvPeriod" width="560" height="160"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-caption">The function f(ℓ) = 2<sup>ℓ</sup> mod 15 is periodic with period r=4. Click to see different x values.</div>
<div class="controls" style="gap:0.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap;">
  <span style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--muted);">x =</span>
  <button class="btn sm active" id="px2" onclick="setPeriodX(2)">x=2</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="px4" onclick="setPeriodX(4)">x=4</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="px7" onclick="setPeriodX(7)">x=7</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="px11" onclick="setPeriodX(11)">x=11</button>
</div>
<div id="periodInfo" style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--ink2);margin-top:0.4rem;min-height:1.2rem;"></div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>The reformulation:</strong> Order-finding (find smallest r with x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1) is equivalent to <strong>period-finding</strong> (find the smallest r such that f(ℓ+r) = f(ℓ)). Period-finding is exactly what the Fourier transform is designed for!
</div>

