<!-- SECTION 5 — CLASSICAL PERIOD FINDING -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s5">
<div class="section-num">Section 05</div>
<h2>Classical Period Finding with FFT</h2>

<p>Since f is periodic with period P, its Fourier transform has peaks at multiples of N/P (where N is the length of the sequence we analyse). This is the classical approach to period finding — and it fails for large n.</p>

<h3>Why the Fourier transform reveals the period</h3>

<p>For continuous signals: a periodic signal x(t) with period T has a Fourier spectrum with peaks at frequencies f₀ = 1/T and its harmonics 2f₀, 3f₀, …. For discrete signals with N points and period P (where P divides N):</p>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">FFT of a Periodic Sequence</div>
  If x<sub>k</sub> = x<sub>k+P</sub> for all k (periodic with period P), then the FFT of x<sub>0</sub>, …, x<sub>N−1</sub> has peaks exactly at positions:
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">
    <div class="eq"><span>m = ℓ · N/P &nbsp;&nbsp; for ℓ = 0, 1, …, P−1</span> &nbsp;&nbsp; (when N mod P = 0)</div>
    <div class="eq"><span>m ≈ ℓ · N/P &nbsp;&nbsp; for ℓ = 0, 1, …, P−1</span> &nbsp;&nbsp; (when N mod P ≠ 0)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Classical algorithm for period finding</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">① Choose N:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Select N &gt; Q where P &lt; Q is a known upper bound (suggest N &gt; Q² for the continued fraction step)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">② Compute:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Build the sequence x₀, x₁, …, x<sub>N−1</sub> where x<sub>k</sub> = f(k). Then compute FFT(x).</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">③ Find peaks:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Identify peak locations M<sub>i</sub> in the spectrum and estimate candidate periods P<sub>i</sub>.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">④ Verify:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Check if x<sub>k</sub> = x<sub>k+P<sub>i</sub></sub> for some i.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">⑤ Repeat:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">If P<sub>i</sub> = P, stop. Otherwise try again.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="warning">
  <strong>Classical complexity:</strong> Step ② requires computing x<sub>k</sub> = f(k) for all k = 0, …, N−1, and then running the FFT. With N ≈ n² (where n is the number of bits of the input), this requires O(N log N) = O(n² log n) operations just for the FFT. But we also need N evaluations of f(k), each costing ~n multiplications modulo n. Total: O(n³) or worse. Crucially, N itself grows as 2<sup>b</sup> (the size of n), making this exponential in b.
</div>

<canvas id="cvFFTperiod" width="560" height="200"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-caption">Classical period finding: the FFT of f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod 15 reveals the period through its peak structure.</div>
<div class="controls" style="gap:0.5rem;">
  <span style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--muted);">x mod 15 =</span>
  <button class="btn sm active" id="fft2" onclick="setFFTx(2)">x=2 (P=4)</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="fft7" onclick="setFFTx(7)">x=7 (P=4)</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="fft4" onclick="setFFTx(4)">x=4 (P=2)</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="fft11" onclick="setFFTx(11)">x=11 (P=2)</button>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 6 — QUANTUM PERIOD FINDING -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s6">
<div class="section-num">Section 06</div>
<h2>Quantum Period Finding with QFT</h2>

<p>The quantum approach uses superposition to evaluate f at all inputs simultaneously, then the QFT to extract the period — using only O(n²) quantum gates total.</p>

<h3>The quantum circuit</h3>

<p>We need two registers. We know P &lt; n, so we choose N &gt; n² to ensure the continued fraction step works. The upper register uses log₂ N qubits and the lower register uses ⌈log₂ n⌉ qubits.</p>

<div class="math-block" style="padding:1.2rem;">
  <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.8rem;line-height:2.3;">
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:90px 1fr;gap:0.2rem 0.5rem;align-items:center;">
      <div style="color:var(--muted);">log₂N qubits</div>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="border:1px solid var(--line);padding:0.15rem 0.3rem;border-radius:2px;color:var(--muted);">|0⟩</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--accent);padding:0.2rem 0.5rem;border-radius:3px;color:var(--accent);font-weight:700;">H<sup>⊗n</sup></div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--purple);padding:0.2rem 0.7rem;border-radius:3px;color:var(--purple);font-weight:700;min-width:2rem;text-align:center;">U<sub>f</sub></div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--green);padding:0.2rem 0.7rem;border-radius:3px;color:var(--green);font-weight:700;">QFT<sub>N</sub></div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--red);padding:0.2rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;color:var(--red);">M</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">M</span>
      </div>
      <div style="color:var(--muted);">⌈log₂n⌉ qubits</div>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="border:1px solid var(--line);padding:0.15rem 0.3rem;border-radius:2px;color:var(--muted);">|0⟩</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:1.3rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:calc(2rem + 0.5rem + 1px);background:#ccc;"></div>
        <span style="font-size:0.7rem;color:var(--muted);">f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n</span>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--red);padding:0.2rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;color:var(--red);">M</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:#ccc;"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--orange);font-weight:600;">f(a)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:0.5rem;font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--muted);">Upper register: stores superposition of all ℓ values. Lower register: stores f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n.</div>
</div>

<h3>State evolution — step by step</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--accent);">|ψ₀⟩:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Both registers start at |0⟩:<br>
      |ψ₀⟩ = |0⟩ ⊗ |0⟩
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--accent);">After H<sup>⊗n</sup>:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Apply Hadamard to every qubit of the upper register:<br>
      |ψ₀⟩ = <span class="c-b">|0⟩</span> ⊗ <span class="scalar">1/√N</span> Σ<sub>k=0</sub><sup>N−1</sup>|k⟩ &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">(uniform superposition of all k)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--purple);">After U<sub>f</sub>:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      The oracle U<sub>f</sub> computes f(k) = x<sup>k</sup> mod n and stores it in the lower register:<br>
      |ψ₁⟩ = <span class="scalar">1/√N</span> Σ<sub>k=0</sub><sup>N−1</sup> |f(k)⟩|k⟩
      &nbsp;&nbsp; = <span class="scalar">1/√N</span> Σ<sub>k</sub> |x<sup>k</sup> mod n⟩|k⟩
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--orange);">Measure lower register:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Suppose we measure f(a) for some 0 ≤ a &lt; P. The state collapses to: <br>
      |ψ₂⟩ ∝ Σ<sub>ℓ</sub> |f(a)⟩|a + ℓP⟩<br>
      <span class="eq-note">The upper register now contains a superposition of <em>only those k values where f(k) = f(a)</em>, i.e. k = a, a+P, a+2P, … — a uniform superposition over an arithmetic progression with step P!</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--green);">After QFT:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Apply QFT<sub>N</sub> to the upper register. A periodic state with period P transforms to peaks at multiples of N/P:<br>
      |ψ₃⟩ → peaks at 0, N/P, 2N/P, …, (P−1)N/P
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>The magic:</strong> Even though we don't know P, the QFT automatically picks it out! The measurement on the lower register (which we don't even need to know the result of!) collapses the state into a periodic superposition with the exact period P we're looking for. The QFT then turns that period into frequency peaks that we can measure.
</div>

