      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkSuperposQFT('a61','a62','fb61')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintShor('h61')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h61">H<sup>⊗n</sup>|0⟩ = (1/√N)Σ|k⟩. N basis states, each with amplitude 1/√N.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb61"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 7 — READING THE PERIOD -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s7">
<div class="section-num">Section 07</div>
<h2>Reading the Period from the Measurement</h2>

<p>After measuring the upper register, we get some value M. We need to extract P from M. There are two cases depending on whether N is divisible by P.</p>

<h3>Case 1: N mod P = 0 (exact case)</h3>

<p>The QFT produces peaks exactly at positions 0, N/P, 2N/P, …, (P−1)·N/P. If we measure position M, we know:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">From M:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">M = ℓ · N/P for some integer ℓ, so M/N = ℓ/P</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Compute C:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">C = M/N = ℓ/P &nbsp;&nbsp; (a fraction we can compute)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Extract P:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      If gcd(P, ℓ) = 1: reduce C to lowest terms → denominator = P<br>
      Otherwise: need another measurement and take lcm of denominators.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="math-block" style="background:var(--blue-hl);border:1px solid #bcd0e8;">
  <div class="mx-label" style="color:var(--accent);font-weight:600;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Example: N = 240, P = 20, N/P = 12</div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Suppose M = 96:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">ℓ = M/(N/P) = 96/12 = 8, so M/N = 8/20 = 2/5</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">But gcd(20,8) = 4 ≠ 1:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">2/5 is not P — the denominator gives P/gcd(P,ℓ) = 20/4 = 5, not 20. Need another measurement!</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">With two measurements M₁, M₂:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">P = lcm(denominators of M₁/N and M₂/N in lowest terms)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Case 2: N mod P ≠ 0 (approximate case)</h3>

<p>The peaks are no longer exactly at integer positions. We measure M ≈ ℓ · N/P + ε, so M/N ≈ ℓ/P + ε/N. We need to find a fraction with small denominator P &lt; N that approximates M/N well.</p>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Continued Fraction Method</div>
  Any rational number can be written as a continued fraction:
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">
    <div class="eq">
      M/N = q₀ + 1/(q₁ + 1/(q₂ + 1/…))
    </div>
  </div>
  where q₀ = ⌊M/N⌋ and the q<sub>i</sub> are computed by the Euclidean algorithm. Truncating this expansion at some point gives a rational approximation with a small denominator. The denominator of that approximation is our estimate of P.
</div>

<h3>Continued fraction algorithm</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Start:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Set r₀ = M (numerator), r₁ = N (denominator)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Step i:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">q<sub>i</sub> = ⌊r<sub>i</sub>/r<sub>i+1</sub>⌋ and r<sub>i+2</sub> = r<sub>i</sub> mod r<sub>i+1</sub></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Stop when:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">r<sub>n</sub>/r<sub>n+1</sub> is very small (the remainder becomes negligible) — truncate there</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="math-block" style="background:var(--green-hl);border:1px solid #6ee7b7;">
  <div class="mx-label" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Example: N = 256, P = 10, M = 77</div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Compute M/N:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">77/256 = 0 + 1/(256/77)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">256/77:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">q₀=0, q₁=⌊256/77⌋=3, remainder r₂=256 mod 77=25</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">77/25:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">q₂=⌊77/25⌋=3, remainder r₃=77 mod 25=2</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">25/2:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">q₃=12, remainder 1 — and 2/25 is tiny, so we stop here</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Result:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Truncating at q₁: 1/(3 + 1/3) = 1/(10/3) = 3/10 &nbsp;&nbsp; <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">→ P = 10 ✓</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Exercise 7.1 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 7.1</span><span class="ex-title">Reading P from M/N</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>N = 1024, P = 4. We measure M = 768. Compute M/N in lowest terms and identify P.</p>
  </div>
