</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 9 — COMPLEXITY -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s9">
<div class="section-num">Section 09</div>
<h2>Complexity of Shor's Algorithm</h2>

<p>Let b = log₂ n be the number of bits of the number we want to factor. We analyze each component.</p>

<h3>Component analysis</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">QFT size:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      log₂ N ≈ log₂ n² = 2 log₂ n = 2b qubits<br>
      QFT gates: O((log₂ N)²) = O((2b)²) = O(b²)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Oracle U<sub>f</sub>:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Computes f(k) = x<sup>k</sup> mod n via repeated squaring.<br>
      Each multiplication mod n takes ~b² classical operations → quantum gates.<br>
      We need ~log₂ N = 2b multiplications.<br>
      Total: O(b²) · O(b) = O(b³) gates for U<sub>f</sub>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Continued fractions:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">O(b²) classical post-processing (Euclidean algorithm)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Total Complexity of Shor's Algorithm</div>
  <div class="math-block">
    <div class="mstep">
      <div class="mstep-label">Shor (quantum):</div>
      <div class="mstep-body" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">O(b³) = O((log₂ n)³) gates — polynomial!</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mstep">
      <div class="mstep-label">Best classical:</div>
      <div class="mstep-body" style="color:var(--red);">O(e<sup>b<sup>1/3</sup>(log b)<sup>2/3</sup></sup>) — sub-exponential, NOT polynomial</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  For RSA-1024: classical requires >2<sup>80</sup> operations (infeasible for any classical computer), while Shor's requires ~10⁹ quantum gate operations — feasible for a sufficiently large quantum computer.
</div>

<canvas id="cvShorComp" width="560" height="230"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-caption">Complexity comparison: Shor's algorithm O(b³) vs classical sub-exponential O(e^(b^(1/3))). Drag to see at different bit sizes b.</div>
<div class="controls">
  <label>b (bits) = <input type="range" id="slBits" min="10" max="100" value="30" oninput="updateShorComp()"></label>
  <span class="ctrl-val" id="bitsVal">30</span>
</div>
<div id="shorCompInfo" style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--ink2);margin-top:0.4rem;min-height:1.5rem;"></div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>The quantum advantage is not just polynomial vs exponential — it breaks cryptography:</strong>
  RSA-2048, the current security standard, would take ~10⁷⁰ operations classically but ~10¹² quantum gate operations with Shor's algorithm. A fault-tolerant quantum computer with ~4000 logical qubits could factor RSA-2048 in hours. This is why post-quantum cryptography (lattice-based, code-based schemes) is actively being standardized.
</div>

<!-- Exercise 9.1 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 9.1</span><span class="ex-title">Qubit count for RSA</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>To factor an RSA-1024 number (b=1024 bits), Shor's algorithm needs approximately 2b qubits for the upper register. What is that qubit count?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
